<CLR_EXEC>.llm_response: The explanation was generated using the Integrated Gradients technique. This method helps to understand which parts of the input image contributed most to the AI system's prediction. The image on the left shows the original input, while the image on the right highlights the attributions for the target class. The color intensity indicates the importance of different regions in the image for the prediction, with brighter areas having a higher impact. In addition to Integrated Gradients, the Isee Platform offers several other explainers that can be used to understand image predictions. For instance, the '/Images/GradientInput' method is a gradient-based technique that computes attributions by taking the partial derivatives of the output with respect to the input and multiplying them with the input itself. This method is designed to improve the sharpness of attribution maps. Users can also explore the '/Images/SmoothGrad' explainer, which averages the gradient at several points corresponding to small perturbations around the point of interest, helping to reduce visual noise and improve explanations. Similarly, '/Images/SquareGrad' and '/Images/VarGrad' offer alternative approaches by averaging the square of the gradient and returning the variance of the gradient, respectively. These explainers are available on the Isee Platform, and users are encouraged to try them out to gain deeper insights into their model predictions.
